  "prompt": "Who all can apply the title \"Er.\" as a prefix for their names?",
  "response": "The prefix \"Er.\" is an abbreviation for \"Engineer\" and is used in some countries, such as India, as a professional title. In India, the title \"Er.\" can be used by graduates of engineering disciplines who are registered with the Institution of Engineers (India) or other recognized professional engineering bodies. \n\nTo be eligible to use the \"Er.\" prefix in India, an individual typically needs to meet the following criteria:\n\n1. **Educational Qualification**: Possess a degree in engineering or technology from a recognized university or institution.\n2. **Membership**: Be a member of a recognized professional engineering body, such as the Institution of Engineers (India).\n\nIn other countries, the usage and eligibility criteria for similar engineering titles may vary. For example, in the United Kingdom, engineers might use titles like \"Eng.\" or \"CEng\" if they are registered with the Engineering Council.\n\nIt's important to check with the relevant professional bodies in your country to understand the specific qualifications and requirements needed to use an engineering title.",
